abstract: Twenty-four hours after having lured Dave Winfield to the Yankees with the richest contract in baseball history, George Steinbrenner began yesterday an effort to keep Reggie Jackson with the team after next season. And today Steinbrenner, the team's principal owner, will try to decide if he wants to keep Ron Guidry as well.
headline_main: Steinbrenner Turns To Wooing Jackson; Wants to Stay 'Forever' Steinbrenner Turns to Jackson 'I've Done Some Things'

abstract: The Utah Jazz tried to take on the Knicks last night with a two-man team: Adrian Dantley, the league's top scorer, and Darrell Griffith, the National Basketball Association's topscoring rookie.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 14--Congressional Republican leaders today pronounced "dead" a proposed pay increase for members of Congress and senior Government officials that President-elect Ronald Reagan had requested.

abstract: IN his annual state-of-the-game message to the baseball brass assembled in Dallas, Bowie Kuhn struck a familiar note of doom. Unless "the most  buoyant urge to win" gave ground to "sanity in player salaries," said the commissioner, financial disaster lay ahead.
headline_main: Sports of The Times; The Prophet of Doom Is Heard Again

abstract: CHOOSING life insurance can be a time-consuming and bewildering task, and now a group of state regulators--charged with  helping consumers make educated purchasing decisions--is suggesting that a model cost disclosure system be abandoned after only four years in existence.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 12--The men designated to be the two top economic officers in the Reagan administration met with senior Republican Senators today and were told that the 1981 Federal budget would exceed $662 billion, $30 billion more than the sum authorized by Congress last month.

abstract: DALLAS, Dec. 12--The battle between the Mets and the Yankees, who were already fighting over Dave Winfield, escalated for a while tonight into a second fight, this one for Fred Lynn.
